    {% block content %}
    <img style="height: auto; width: 100%;" src="/static/images/background.jpg">
        <center>
            <h1 style="color:white; margin-top: -700px; font-weight: 1000px; font-family:'Courier New', Courier, monospace; font-size: 50px;"><b>About</b></h1><br>
            <p style="color:rgb(242, 255, 0); font-family:'Courier New', Courier, monospace;"><b>
                Monkeypox, a viral zoonotic disease, has emerged as a significant public health concern due to its potential for human-to-human transmission and the lack of specific antiviral treatments. Timely and accurate diagnosis is crucial for effective management and control of outbreaks. In this study, we propose a novel approach for Monkeypox diagnosis using interpretable deep learning techniques. Our proposed model leverages deep neural networks to analyze clinical data, including symptoms, laboratory test results, and epidemiological information, to classify patients as either Monkeypox-positive or negative. Unlike traditional black-box deep learning models, our approach emphasizes interpretability, allowing healthcare professionals to understand the underlying reasoning behind the model's predictions. Through extensive experimentation on real-world datasets, we demonstrate the efficacy of our proposed method in accurately diagnosing Monkeypox cases. Moreover, by providing interpretable insights into the decision-making process, our model enhances clinical decision support and enables healthcare practitioners to make informed decisions regarding patient management and outbreak control strategies. Overall, our study presents a promising framework for Monkeypox diagnosis, combining the power of deep learning with interpretable techniques to improve diagnostic accuracy and aid in the effective management of Monkeypox outbreaks.
            </b></p>
        </center>
